,"1124":"1124","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1122":"1122","1166":"1166","about 1120":"about 1120","Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dunbar, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hirsel,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz.","South German and Swiss German: from a diminutive of   Hirz  . Compare   Hirtzel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hirtzel","meanings":["South German and Swiss German: variant of   Hirzel   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. Compare   Hartzell   1 and   Hertzel   2."]},{"name":"Hirz","meanings":["German: variant of   Hirsch   1. Compare   Hirtz  ."]}]},{"name":"Deirdre","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name borne in Celtic legend by a tragic heroine, sometimes referred to as ‘Deirdre of the Sorrows’. The story goes that she was betrothed to Conchobhar, King of Ulster, but instead eloped with her beloved Naoise. Eventually, however, the jilted king murdered Naoise and his brothers, and Deirdre herself died of a broken heart. She is sometimes taken as symbolic of the fate of Ireland under English rule, but this has not stopped her name being used by English parents with no Celtic blood in them. It became popular in Ireland and elsewhere in the Edwardian era, following retellings of the legend by both the poet  W. B. Yeats  (  1907 ) and the playwright  J. M. Synge  (  1910 ). The name itself is of uncertain derivation; the earliest Celtic forms are very variable."],"variants":[{"name":"Deidre","meanings":["Name borne in Celtic legend by a tragic heroine, sometimes referred to as ‘Deirdre of the Sorrows’. The story goes that she was betrothed to Conchobhar, King of Ulster, but instead eloped with her beloved Naoise. Eventually, however, the jilted king murdered Naoise and his brothers, and Deirdre herself died of a broken heart. She is sometimes taken as symbolic of the fate of Ireland under English rule, but this has not stopped her name being used by English parents with no Celtic blood in them. It became popular in Ireland and elsewhere in the Edwardian era, following retellings of the legend by both the poet  W. B. Yeats  (  1907 ) and the playwright  J. M. Synge  (  1910 ). The name itself is of uncertain derivation; the earliest Celtic forms are very variable."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Heiress of Hirsel and Greenlaw Deirdre Hirsel, was born in 1094, in Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland as the daughter of Unknown. She married Gospatric III of Dunbar about 1120, in Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died from 1124 to 1131, in her hometown."},"et":{"1094–from 1124 to 1131":"1094–1124 kuni 1131","1094–1131":"1094–1131","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1122–1182":"1122–1182","1124–1201":"1124–1201","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1135–1154":"1135–1154","–Male":"Surnud","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","from 1124 to 1131":"1124 kuni 1131","1094":"1094","1182":"1182","1124":"1124","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1122":"1122","1166":"1166","about 1120":"umbes 1120","Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dunbar, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1094–from 1124 to 1131":"1094–vuodesta 1124 vuoteen 1131","1094–1131":"1094–1131","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1122–1182":"1122–1182","1124–1201":"1124–1201","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1135–1154":"1135–1154","–Male":"Kuollut","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","from 1124 to 1131":"vuodesta 1124 vuoteen 1131","1094":"1094","1182":"1182","1124":"1124","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1122":"1122","1166":"1166","about 1120":"noin 1120","Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dunb